Data Analysis 3 - Assignment 2¶

The aim of the project is to create a predictive model, which is able to price mid-size apartments hosting 2-6 guests in Milan. The model will be chosen from 3 (4) different models, using different prediction methods. The four models are created with OLS, Lasso, Random Forest and GBM

In [ ]:
# convert bathrooms_text to float
# def function to clean the bathroom text, split and space and set to int, if not possible set to 1
def clean_bathroom(text):
    try:
        return float(text.split(" ")[0])
    except:
        return text == 0.5

# apply function to the column
data["bathrooms"] = data["bathrooms_text"].apply(clean_bathroom)
data.drop(columns="bathrooms_text", inplace=True)

An important change to the code used in class is the use of availabilty of accomodations. These variables show that out of the next 30, 60, 90, 365 days, how many are available for booking. An accomodation can be either unavailable because the host block out a timeframe for some alternative use to lending or because it's already booked. The assumption during this project is that this show the demand for the apartment and can be used as a predictor.

To deal with amenities, dummies are created from the 50 most frequent ones:

In [ ]:
import ast

# Clean amenities column
data['new_amenities'] = data['amenities'].apply(lambda x: ast.literal_eval(x)) 

# Create a list of all amenities
all_amenities = []

for lst in data['new_amenities']:
    for amenity in lst:
        all_amenities.append(amenity)

# Create a series of the 50 most frequent amenities
top50_amenities = pd.Series(all_amenities).value_counts().head(50)

# Create a list of the top 50 amenities
amenities_list = top50_amenities.index.tolist()

# Create a variable for each top 100 amenity starting with "d_"
for my_amenities in amenities_list:
    data['da_' + my_amenities] = data['new_amenities'].apply(lambda x: 1 if my_amenities in x else 0)

# Rename columns, as amenities can have spaces and uppercase characters
data.columns = [name.replace(' ', '_').replace("","").replace("-","").replace("","").replace(":","").replace("/","_").lower() for name in data.columns]

# Drop the original amenities column
data = data.drop(columns=['amenities', 'new_amenities'])

# first create flags for missing variables, then input with median.

data = data.assign(
    # flag for superhost
    flag_host_is_superhost=np.multiply(data.d_host_is_superhost.isna(), 1),
    d_host_is_superhost=data.d_host_is_superhost.fillna(np.median(data.d_host_is_superhost.dropna())),

    # flag for response rate
    #flag_host_response_rate=np.multiply(data.p_host_response_rate.isna(), 1),
    #p_host_response_rate=data.p_host_response_rate.fillna(np.median(data.p_host_response_rate.dropna())),

    # flag for acceptance rate
    flag_host_acceptance_rate=np.multiply(data.p_host_acceptance_rate.isna(), 1),
    p_host_acceptance_rate=data.p_host_acceptance_rate.fillna(np.median(data.p_host_acceptance_rate.dropna())),

    # flag for beds
    flag_beds=np.multiply(data.n_beds.isna(), 1),
    n_beds=data.n_beds.fillna(np.median(data.n_beds.dropna())),
    # flag for bedrooms 
    flag_bedrooms=np.multiply(data.n_bedrooms.isna(), 1),
    n_bedrooms=data.n_bedrooms.fillna(np.median(data.n_bedrooms.dropna())),
    # flag for accuracy score
    flag_review_scores_rating=np.multiply(data.n_review_scores_accuracy.isna(), 1),
    n_review_scores_accuracy=data.n_review_scores_accuracy.fillna(
        np.median(data.n_review_scores_accuracy.dropna())),
    # flag for cleaniness reviews
    flag_review_scores_cleanliness=np.multiply(data.n_review_scores_cleanliness.isna(), 1),
    n_review_scores_cleanliness=data.n_review_scores_cleanliness.fillna(
        np.median(data.n_review_scores_cleanliness.dropna())),
    # flag for checkin reviews
    flag_review_scores_checkin=np.multiply(data.n_review_scores_checkin.isna(), 1),
    n_review_scores_checkin=data.n_review_scores_checkin.fillna(
        np.median(data.n_review_scores_checkin.dropna())),
    # flag for communication reviews
    flag_review_scores_communication=np.multiply(data.n_review_scores_communication.isna(), 1),
    n_review_scores_communication=data.n_review_scores_communication.fillna(
        np.median(data.n_review_scores_communication.dropna())),
    # flag for location reviews
    flag_review_scores_location=np.multiply(data.n_review_scores_location.isna(), 1),
    n_review_scores_location=data.n_review_scores_location.fillna(
        np.median(data.n_review_scores_location.dropna())),
    # flag for value reviews
    flag_review_scores_value=np.multiply(data.n_review_scores_value.isna(), 1),
    n_review_scores_value=data.n_review_scores_value.fillna(
        np.median(data.n_review_scores_value.dropna())),
)

# Create the ggplot object
df_var_imp_cutoff = df_var_imp[df_var_imp.imp > cutoff]

# Sort the DataFrame by 'imp' values in descending order
df_var_imp_cutoff_sorted = df_var_imp_cutoff.sort_values(by='imp', ascending=False)

df_var_imp_cutoff_sorted['variable'] = pd.Categorical(df_var_imp_cutoff_sorted['variable'], 
                                                      categories=df_var_imp_cutoff_sorted['variable'], 
                                                      ordered=True)

df_var_imp_cutoff_sorted['variable'] = df_var_imp_cutoff_sorted['variable'].cat.reorder_categories(
    df_var_imp_cutoff_sorted['variable'].cat.categories[::-1])

plot = (ggplot(df_var_imp_cutoff_sorted, aes(x='variable', y='imp'))
        + geom_bar(stat='identity', fill='blue')
        + theme_minimal()
        + ggtitle('Random forest model highest feature importances')
        + labs(x='Variables', y='Importance')
        + coord_flip()
       )

# Print the plot
